(1, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'the days of Adam after he had begotten Seth', 4, 47, 'connection', 'Link to Life Span', 'This phrase highlights the longevity of Adam''s life, paralleling the extended lifespans of early patriarchs in Genesis. For example, Genesis 6:3 notes God''s decision to limit human lifespan to 120 years, indicating a shift in divine allowance. This comparison emphasizes the unique nature of pre-Flood life and the eventual decline of human longevity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s declaration to limit human lifespan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'and he begat sons and daughters', 74, 105, 'theology', 'Family and Legacy', 'This passage suggests the importance of family and procreation in God''s creation plan. Many scholars believe that the mention of Adam''s sons and daughters underscores the idea that humanity is intended to multiply and fill the earth (Genesis 1:28). It reflects God''s blessing on family and the continuation of life through generations.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s command to multiply and fill the earth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'after he had begotten Seth', 21, 47, 'question', 'Significance of Seth', 'What does the birth of Seth signify for the lineage of humanity? Seth is seen as a replacement for Abel, who was murdered by Cain, suggesting themes of redemption and continuation of God''s promise. How do these themes of renewal and hope impact your understanding of your own family legacy?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'eight hundred years', 53, 72, 'greek', 'Significance of Time', 'אֶת־שְׁמוֹ (et-sh''mo, H8034) - ''name'' or ''fame.'' The significance of Adam''s long life is not just in years lived but in the legacy and influence he left behind. This invites reflection on how we use our time to shape the lives of those around us.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8034", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word ''name.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'And all the days that Adam lived were nine hundred and thirty years: and he died.', 0, 81, 'connection', 'Adam''s Lifespan Comparison', 'The mention of Adam''s lifespan in this verse can be cross-referenced with Genesis 11:32, where the ages of the patriarchs are also noted. This connection highlights the longevity of early human life and sets a pattern for the ages recorded in the genealogies. Understanding these lifespans can deepen our awareness of the early human experience and God''s unfolding plan through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:32", "description": "Lifespan comparison of patriarchs"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 69, 81, 'theology', 'The Reality of Death', 'This brief but poignant phrase emphasizes the certainty of death as a consequence of sin, reflecting the theological theme of mortality introduced in Genesis 3:19. Many scholars believe this serves as a reminder of humanity''s fallen state and the need for redemption, which is ultimately fulfilled in Christ. It highlights the gravity of sin and the hope of eternal life through faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "The consequence of sin and mortality"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'were nine hundred and thirty years', 33, 67, 'question', 'Understanding Lifespan', 'What does Adam''s long lifespan signify in the context of God''s creation? This prompts reflection on the nature of life, divine purpose, and how the longevity of early humans may inform our understanding of humanity''s relationship with God in the pre-fall world.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 69, 81, 'greek', 'Death in Scripture', 'מוּת (mût, H4191) - to die, perish. This Hebrew term captures the finality of death, which serves as a reminder of the human condition following the Fall. Its repeated use in genealogies emphasizes mortality''s inevitability and the theological implications of sin leading to death.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4191", "description": "Strong''s number for ''to die''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'And Seth lived an hundred and five years, and begat Enos:', 0, 57, 'connection', 'Seth''s Lineage Importance', 'Seth''s role as a progenitor is significant in the biblical narrative as it establishes a lineage leading to Noah and ultimately to Jesus Christ (Luke 3:38). This verse highlights God''s continued work through Seth''s descendants, emphasizing the theme of redemption and preservation in biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 3:38", "description": "Genealogy of Jesus tracing back to Seth"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:25", "description": "Introduction of Seth after Abel''s death"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'begat Enos', 46, 56, 'theology', 'Significance of ''Begat''', 'The term ''begat'' signifies a divine purpose in procreation. Many scholars believe this underscores the importance of lineage in God''s plan for humanity. It reflects the continuity of the covenant promise, showing how God''s faithfulness is carried through generations, ultimately leading to the fulfillment of His redemptive plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of genealogies in Scripture"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'lived an hundred and five years', 9, 40, 'question', 'Reflection on Lifespan', 'What does Seth''s lifespan of 105 years teach us about the value of life and legacy in God''s plan? How should we view our time on earth in light of our contributions to future generations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'Seth lived an hundred and five years', 4, 40, 'greek', 'Hebrew Root of ''Seth''', 'שֵׁת (Shet, H8352) - appointed, placed. The name Seth signifies God''s provision of a righteous line after Abel''s death, illustrating God''s sovereignty in human history.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8352", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Seth"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'Seth lived after he begat Enos eight hundred and seven years, and begat sons and daughters:', 4, 95, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'This verse highlights the generational continuity in the lineage from Adam to Noah. It echoes themes found in Genesis 4:25-26, where Seth''s descendants are highlighted as continuing the faithful line. This connection emphasizes the importance of preserving godly heritage through successive generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:25-26", "description": "Refers to the importance of Seth''s lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'lived after he begat Enos eight hundred and seven years', 9, 64, 'theology', 'Longevity and Divine Favor', 'Many scholars believe that the long lifespans recorded in Genesis reflect God''s favor and the initial state of creation before sin''s full effect. This suggests a divine intention behind human life, portraying longevity as a blessing and a means to fulfill God''s plan through generations.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New Bible Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of lifespan in Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 7, 7, 'kjv', 'and begat sons and daughters:', 66, 95, 'question', 'Family and Legacy', 'What does it mean for us today that Seth had sons and daughters, indicating a legacy beyond just one notable descendant? How does acknowledging the broader family dynamics encourage us to think about our own families and communities in faith?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Seth were nine hundred and twelve years: and he died.', 0, 73, 'connection', 'Longevity in Genesis', 'The mention of Seth''s long lifespan is significant when compared to Genesis 6:3, where God limits human lifespan to 120 years. This connection illustrates the gradual decline of human longevity post-Fall and highlights the extraordinary ages of the patriarchs as a reflection of the pre-Flood world. Understanding this context helps to grasp the biblical narrative of human history and divine interaction.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s decree on human lifespan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'he died.', 65, 73, 'theology', 'The Reality of Death', 'The phrase ''and he died'' serves as a sobering reminder of the mortality of humanity. Many scholars believe this recurring refrain in Genesis highlights the consequences of sin introduced in the Fall (Genesis 3). This theological concept emphasizes the need for redemption and the hope found in Christ, who conquered death (1 Corinthians 15:55-57).', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "The curse of death due to sin"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'nine hundred and twelve years', 30, 59, 'question', 'Understanding Lifespan', 'What is the significance of Seth living nine hundred and twelve years? Reflecting on this, how does the concept of lifespan in the Bible shape your understanding of God''s promises and human purpose? Consider how this extended lifespan contrasts with today’s understanding of life and death.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 8, 8, 'kjv', 'all the days of Seth', 4, 24, 'greek', 'Days of Seth', 'יָמִים (yamim, H3117) - days, time period. This Hebrew term signifies not just the passage of time but also the fullness of life experiences. The use of ''days'' here emphasizes the totality of Seth''s life and God''s sovereignty over its duration.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3117", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for days"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'And Enos lived ninety years, and begat Cainan:', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Lineage Significance', 'The mention of Enos living ninety years before begetting Cainan highlights the importance of genealogical records in Scripture. This lineage is crucial for understanding the fulfillment of God''s promises, as seen in Luke 3:38, where Enos is included in the lineage leading to Jesus. This connection emphasizes the continuity of God''s plan through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 3:38", "description": "Enos included in the genealogy leading to Christ"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'And Enos lived ninety years, and begat Cainan:', 0, 46, 'theology', 'The Nature of Life', 'This passage illustrates the concept of life as a divinely appointed journey toward fulfillment of God''s purpose. Many scholars believe that each generation represents a step in God''s redemptive plan, where the act of begetting signifies both physical and spiritual legacy. Enos, like his forefathers, plays a role in this ongoing narrative.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'And Enos lived ninety years, and begat Cainan:', 0, 46, 'question', 'Reflecting on Generational Impact', 'What does it mean for us today to consider the lives of those who came before us, like Enos? How does recognizing the importance of our lineage influence our understanding of our own purpose in God''s plan?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 9, 9, 'kjv', 'And Enos lived ninety years, and begat Cainan:', 0, 46, 'greek', 'Understanding ''begat''', 'יָלַד (yalad, H3205) - to bear, bring forth. This Hebrew term emphasizes the act of giving life and the continuation of the family line, which is essential in the biblical narrative as it showcases the unfolding plan of God through generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s definition for the term ''to bear''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'after he begat Cainan', 15, 36, 'connection', 'Family Lineage Importance', 'This phrase highlights the significance of genealogy in the Bible, particularly as it relates to God''s covenantal promises. The mention of family lineage connects to Genesis 12:2, where God promises Abraham that he will make him into a great nation, emphasizing the importance of descendants in biblical narratives. Understanding this lineage showcases how God works through families to fulfill His divine purpose.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:2", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham regarding his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'eight hundred and fifteen years', 37, 68, 'theology', 'Longevity and Divine Favor', 'The longevity of Enos, living 815 years, suggests a time when human life spans were significantly longer, which many scholars believe reflects a unique aspect of God''s creation before the Flood. This raises questions about how divine favor and human sinfulness interact, indicating that lifespans may have been shortened as a consequence of the Fall (Genesis 6:3). Such insights encourage reflection on the relationship between obedience to God and the blessings of life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s declaration on human lifespan post-Fall"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 10, 10, 'kjv', 'and begat sons and daughters:', 70, 99, 'question', 'Legacy and Influence', 'What does it mean for us today that Enos not only lived a long life but also had sons and daughters? How does this challenge our understanding of legacy? Reflecting on the way Enos''s life influenced the next generations can lead to insights about our own roles in shaping the faith and values of those who come after us.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Enos were nine hundred and five years: and he died.', 0, 71, 'connection', 'Link to Death in Scripture', 'The phrase ''and he died'' reiterates a recurring theme in Genesis, seen in Genesis 3:19, where God states, ''for dust you are, and to dust you shall return.'' This connection emphasizes the inevitability of death as a consequence of sin, framing Enos'' life within the broader narrative of human mortality.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "God''s declaration of mortality due to sin"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Enos were nine hundred and five years: and he died.', 0, 71, 'theology', 'The Reality of Human Mortality', 'This passage suggests that even the most long-lived figures in the Bible ultimately face death, reflecting the Christian teaching on the fallen state of humanity. Many scholars believe this emphasizes the need for redemption found in Christ, as all people, regardless of their righteousness, share in the common fate of death.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'nine hundred and five years', 30, 57, 'question', 'Significance of Lifespan', 'What does Enos'' lifespan of nine hundred and five years reveal about God''s patience and the nature of human life? How does this long duration challenge our understanding of time and divine purpose in the context of a world marred by sin?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 11, 11, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 59, 71, 'greek', 'Death in the Hebrew Context', 'מוּת (muwth, H4191) - to die, perish. This term encompasses not only physical death but also spiritual separation from God, highlighting the gravity of death in the biblical narrative and its implications for humanity''s relationship with the Creator.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4191", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term for death"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Cainan lived seventy years, and begat Mahalaleel:', 0, 53, 'connection', 'Generational Continuity', 'Cainan''s life and lineage connect to the broader narrative of Genesis, particularly in Genesis 4:25-26, where the importance of names and generational lines is established. This highlights God''s ongoing covenant with humanity through specific individuals, emphasizing the significance of genealogy in redemptive history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 4:25", "description": "Establishes the importance of names and lineage."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 3:36", "description": "Cainan is mentioned in the genealogy of Jesus, connecting Old Testament lineage to New Testament fulfillment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Cainan lived seventy years, and begat Mahalaleel:', 0, 53, 'theology', 'The Value of Life Span', 'The mention of Cainan living seventy years before fathering Mahalaleel suggests a divine purpose in the timing of childbirth, which many scholars believe reflects the theological idea that God ordains the seasons of life. This resonates with the belief that each life contributes to the unfolding of God''s plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s timing and purpose in human generations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'begat Mahalaleel', 36, 52, 'greek', 'Significance of ''begat''', 'While the Old Testament primarily uses Hebrew, the concept of ''begat'' translates to the Hebrew word ''יָלַד'' (yalad, H3205) - to bear or to give birth. This term signifies not just the act of procreation but also the continuation of a lineage and God''s covenantal promises through successive generations.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''begat.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'And Cainan lived seventy years, and begat Mahalaleel:', 0, 53, 'question', 'Reflection on Generational Impact', 'How does Cainan''s decision to have Mahalaleel at seventy years shape your understanding of God''s timing in your own life? What implications does this have for how we view our roles in our families and communities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'And Cainan lived after he begat Mahalaleel eight hundred and forty years, and begat sons and daughters:', 0, 103, 'connection', 'Generations and God’s Promise', 'Cainan''s long life and the continuation of generations reflect God''s promise to populate the earth and bless humanity (Genesis 1:28). This connection emphasizes the faithfulness of God through successive generations, which is a recurring theme in Genesis.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God commands humanity to be fruitful and multiply."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'after he begat Mahalaleel eight hundred and forty years', 17, 72, 'theology', 'Longevity and Divine Favor', 'Many scholars believe the long lifespans in Genesis indicate divine favor and the stability of early human life under God''s creation. This challenges modern understandings of mortality and invites reflection on God’s original design for humanity.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'and begat sons and daughters:', 74, 103, 'question', 'Legacy of Family', 'In what ways does Cainan’s act of ''begatting sons and daughters'' reflect the importance of family in your own life? How can you cultivate a legacy that honors God and passes on faith to future generations?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Cainan were nine hundred and ten years: and he died.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Longevity in Genesis', 'The lifespan of Cainan, noted as nine hundred and ten years, connects to the broader theme of longevity in Genesis. For instance, Genesis 6:3 states that man''s days shall be limited to 120 years, indicating a shift in human lifespan post-Flood. This contrast highlights the unique circumstances of pre-Flood life and raises questions about the impact of sin and divine judgment on human longevity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "Discusses the limitation of human lifespan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 60, 72, 'theology', 'The Certainty of Death', 'The phrase ''and he died'' serves as a reminder of the inevitability of death, a consequence of the Fall (Genesis 3:19). This theological theme underscores the transient nature of human life and the necessity of seeking eternal life through Christ, as articulated in John 3:16. Many scholars believe that recognizing mortality prompts a deeper reflection on the purpose of life and the hope of resurrection.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 3:19", "description": "Introduces the concept of death as a consequence of sin."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 3:16", "description": "Speaks of eternal life through belief in Christ."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Cainan were nine hundred and ten years:', 0, 59, 'question', 'Life Span Reflection', 'What significance do the long lifespans in Genesis hold for our understanding of God''s relationship with humanity? How might Cainan''s extended years challenge us to consider our own lives and the legacy we leave behind?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'And Mahalaleel lived sixty and five years, and begat Jared:', 0, 59, 'connection', 'Generational Significance', 'Mahalaleel''s age at the birth of Jared connects to the genealogy in Luke 3:37, which traces Jesus'' lineage back to Adam. This connection emphasizes the importance of each generation in the unfolding of God''s redemptive plan, highlighting that each individual plays a role in the lineage leading to Christ.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 3:37", "description": "Genealogy of Jesus tracing back to Adam"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'And Mahalaleel lived sixty and five years, and begat Jared:', 0, 59, 'theology', 'Theology of Generations', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the biblical theme of continuity through generations. Each name in the genealogy represents both a historical figure and a theological thread in God''s covenantal promise, emphasizing that God''s plan is fulfilled over time and through various individuals.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'And Mahalaleel lived sixty and five years, and begat Jared:', 0, 59, 'question', 'Reflection on Generational Impact', 'What does it mean for us today to recognize the significance of our own generations? How can we honor the legacy of those who came before us while also considering the impact we have on future generations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'lived after he begat Jared eight hundred and thirty years', 15, 72, 'connection', 'Longevity in Genesis', 'The long lifespans of the patriarchs, as seen with Mahalaleel''s 830 years after Jared, echo the themes of Genesis 6:3, where God limits human lifespan to 120 years. These extended lives symbolize the closeness of the pre-flood world to God, suggesting a time of purity and direct relationship. Understanding this context helps illuminate the significance of lifespan as a theological element in the narrative.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 6:3", "description": "God''s decree on human lifespan"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'begat sons and daughters', 78, 102, 'theology', 'Family and Legacy', 'This phrase reflects the biblical emphasis on family and progeny as part of God''s creation mandate (Genesis 1:28). Many scholars believe that the mention of ''sons and daughters'' underscores the importance of lineage and community in sustaining faith and practice across generations, aligning with the broader theological narrative of God''s covenant with humanity.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:28", "description": "God''s command to be fruitful and multiply"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And Mahalaleel lived', 0, 20, 'question', 'Meaning of Life Span', 'What does Mahalaleel''s long life signify about God''s design for humanity and our purpose on earth? How might understanding the context of these lifetimes affect our view of time and legacy in our own lives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'And all the days of Mahalaleel were eight hundred ninety and five years: and he died.', 0, 85, 'connection', 'Life Span Comparisons', 'Mahalaleel''s long life of 895 years parallels the extraordinary lifespans of other early patriarchs, such as Adam (Genesis 5:5) and Methuselah (Genesis 5:27). These lengthy lives signify the early human experience and may reflect God''s original design for human longevity before the Fall. The gradual decline in lifespans post-Flood suggests a shift in the human condition and divine order.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:5", "description": "Adam''s lifespan as a comparison."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:27", "description": "Methuselah''s notable lifespan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and he died.', 73, 85, 'theology', 'The Certainty of Death', 'The phrase ''and he died'' serves as a sober reminder of mortality, echoing the theological principle that death entered the world through sin (Romans 5:12). Many scholars believe this underscores humanity''s frailty and the universal consequence of sin, prompting reflection on the nature of life, death, and the hope of resurrection through Christ.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 5:12", "description": "Theological insight into sin and death."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'all the days of Mahalaleel', 4, 30, 'question', 'Understanding Life''s Duration', 'What does the specific mention of ''all the days of Mahalaleel'' reveal about the value of a life lived in faithfulness? How can we apply this understanding to our own lives, recognizing that each day is a gift from God?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 5, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'were eight hundred ninety and five years', 31, 71, 'greek', 'Lifespan Significance', 'חַי (chai, H2425) - life, living. This Hebrew term emphasizes the quality and intention of life as a divine gift. Mahalaleel''s lifespan reflects not just a number but a life filled with purpose and relation to God, reinforcing the biblical theme of life as sacred.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2425", "description": "Strong''s number for ''life''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');